00:18:57,650 --> 00:19:01,920
The Universe was created during the Big Bang,
it is expanding.

217
00:19:01,920 --> 00:19:06,050
Galaxies further away from us are closer to
the Big Bang epoch,

218
00:19:06,050 --> 00:19:09,350
they are younger than the galaxies close to
our own.

219
00:19:09,350 --> 00:19:15,320
If we establish a morphological classification
as a function of the distance,

220
00:19:15,320 --> 00:19:20,000
in the same time we establish a morphological
classification as a function of the age of

221
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:23,230
the Universe.
Observing at various distances,

222
00:19:23,230 --> 00:19:29,160
we observe different epochs of the Universe.
Here we have a morphological classification

223
00:19:29,160 --> 00:19:32,340
giving
the percentage of each type of galaxy in the

224
00:19:32,340 --> 00:19:41,440
local universe:
3% are elliptical galaxies,

225
00:19:41,440 --> 00:19:50,150
15% are lenticular galaxies,
72% - spiral galaxies, the majority are spiral

226
00:19:50,150 --> 00:19:53,770
galaxies,
and 10% corresponding to galaxies that we

227
00:19:53,770 --> 00:19:57,591
are not able to classify.
This is one of the observational facts, another

228
00:19:57,591 --> 00:20:00,750
one tells us that
if the same observations are obtained for

229
00:20:00,750 --> 00:20:04,890
galaxies further away
the results are not the same. Previously there

230
00:20:04,890 --> 00:20:10,790
was 72% of the spiral galaxies
now the spiral galaxies represent only 31%.

231
00:20:10,790 --> 00:20:16,260
The galaxies that are not classified represent
32% of the observed galaxies.

232
00:20:16,260 --> 00:20:19,780
These are the galaxies that are
at a different evolutionary stage than in

233
00:20:19,780 --> 00:20:25,080
here.
Those morphological classifications can be

234
00:20:25,080 --> 00:20:28,180
established
as a function of distance regardless the theoretical

235
00:20:28,180 --> 00:20:32,850
tools
at our disposal used to understand the observations.

236
00:20:32,850 --> 00:20:35,600
It is essential that those theoretical tools
relate

237
00:20:35,600 --> 00:20:40,810
at the same time the morphological classification
as a function of the distance,

238
00:20:40,810 --> 00:20:45,540
masses determined using the measures of the
Doppler effect

239
00:20:45,540 --> 00:20:50,030
and the rotational velocities of galaxies.
They also have to relate to the study of the

240
00:20:50,030 --> 00:20:54,670
stellar populations
that uses for example

241
00:20:54,670 --> 00:20:57,630
the colour-magnitude diagrams of the resolved
stars

242
00:20:57,630 --> 00:21:01,670
from various regions in galaxies also as a
function of the distance.

243
00:21:01,670 --> 00:21:07,530
Currently, the studies of the formation
and evolutions of galaxies make great progress

244
00:21:07,530 --> 00:21:11,390
from the theoretical as well as
observational point of view.

245
00:21:11,390 --> 00:21:17,110
We have access to bigger and bigger telescopes
that enable us to study galaxies

246
00:21:17,110 --> 00:21:20,890
which are further and further away, as the
telescopes gather more and more light.

247
00:21:20,890 --> 00:21:26,970
It is possible to study galaxies
with weaker and weaker intrinsic flux.

248
00:21:26,970 --> 00:21:31,880
And it is not all. In addition to large telescopes
there are smaller ones that specialise

249
00:21:31,880 --> 00:21:38,280
in detailed cartography of large fraction
of the Universe,

250
00:21:38,280 --> 00:21:44,270
maybe even the whole Universe.
It is possible to study large samples of galaxies

251
00:21:44,270 --> 00:21:48,730
and with the obtained statistical properties,
from the observational point of view,

252
00:21:48,730 --> 00:21:54,280
and with progress in the data processing
and on the theoretical side as well,

253
00:21:54,280 --> 00:21:58,700
one can create simulations of entire "chunks"
of Universe containing

254
00:21:58,700 --> 00:22:02,410
billions of particles that are subject to
gravitational forces,

255
00:22:02,410 --> 00:22:08,290
pressure and even shock waves
created by supernovae explosions in galaxies.

256
00:22:08,290 --> 00:22:14,420
It is now possible to confront theory and
observations

257
00:22:14,420 --> 00:22:18,200
and to draw some conclusions about the validity
of theoretical models.

